---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro'
import Disclaimer from '../../components/Disclaimer.astro'
import VerifyBadge from '../../components/VerifyBadge.astro'
---

<Base
  title="Banking in Bermuda for Expats"
  description="A guide to banking in Bermuda for expats: the main banks, account opening requirements, the Bermuda Dollar, fees, international transfers, and US account restrictions."
>
  <section class="hero" style="padding-block: var(--space-16);">
    <div class="hero__inner">
      <nav aria-label="Breadcrumb">
        <ol class="breadcrumb" style="justify-content: center; color: rgba(255,255,255,0.6);">
          <li><a href="/Pilot.BM/" style="color: rgba(255,255,255,0.6);">Home</a></li>
          <li class="breadcrumb__sep" aria-hidden="true">›</li>
          <li><a href="/Pilot.BM/move" style="color: rgba(255,255,255,0.6);">Moving</a></li>
          <li class="breadcrumb__sep" aria-hidden="true">›</li>
          <li style="color: rgba(255,255,255,0.9);">Banking</li>
        </ol>
      </nav>
      <h1 class="hero-title">Banking in Bermuda</h1>
      <p class="hero-subtitle">
        The main banks, what you need to open an account as a non-Bermudian,
        the currency situation, and one issue that surprises almost every US expat.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="container" style="padding-block: var(--space-12);">
    <div style="max-width: 800px; margin: 0 auto;">

      <!-- REQUIRED disclaimer above the fold -->
      <Disclaimer variant="relocation" />

      <!-- Main banks -->
      <h2 style="margin-top: var(--space-8);">The main banks</h2>
      <p>
        Bermuda has a small but fully functional banking sector. Three banks serve the retail
        and corporate market for residents:
      </p>

      <div style="margin-bottom: var(--space-8);">

        <div style="border: 1px solid var(--color-border); border-radius: var(--radius-md); padding: var(--space-5) var(--space-6); margin-bottom: var(--space-4);">
          <h3 style="margin-bottom: var(--space-2);">Butterfield Bank</h3>
          <p style="margin-bottom: var(--space-2);">
            Bermuda's premier local bank and the dominant choice for residents and expats.
            Butterfield has been operating in Bermuda since 1858 and has a well-regarded reputation
            for service, stability, and its understanding of the local market. Most expats in
            the international business sector bank with Butterfield. It offers personal accounts,
            mortgage lending, investment services, and corporate banking.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); margin: 0;">
            <a href="https://www.butterfieldgroup.com/bermuda" rel="noopener" target="_blank">butterfieldgroup.com/bermuda</a>
          </p>
        </div>

        <div style="border: 1px solid var(--color-border); border-radius: var(--radius-md); padding: var(--space-5) var(--space-6); margin-bottom: var(--space-4);">
          <h3 style="margin-bottom: var(--space-2);">HSBC Bermuda</h3>
          <p style="margin-bottom: var(--space-2);">
            HSBC operates in Bermuda as part of its global network, which is useful for expats
            who already bank with HSBC internationally or who expect to maintain accounts in
            multiple countries. HSBC Bermuda offers personal and business accounts, and the
            global network can simplify international transfers in some cases.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); margin: 0;">
            <a href="https://www.hsbc.bm" rel="noopener" target="_blank">hsbc.bm</a>
          </p>
        </div>

        <div style="border: 1px solid var(--color-border); border-radius: var(--radius-md); padding: var(--space-5) var(--space-6);">
          <h3 style="margin-bottom: var(--space-2);">Clarien Bank</h3>
          <p style="margin-bottom: var(--space-2);">
            Clarien is a smaller Bermudian bank offering personal and private banking services.
            It is a viable option, particularly for clients seeking more personalised relationship
            banking. Worth considering if Butterfield or HSBC do not meet your specific needs.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); margin: 0;">
            <a href="https://www.clarienbank.com" rel="noopener" target="_blank">clarienbank.com</a>
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Account opening -->
      <h2 style="margin-top: var(--space-8);">Opening an account — what you will need</h2>
      <p>
        Opening a bank account in Bermuda as a non-Bermudian requires documentation and takes time.
        <strong>Allow 2–4 weeks</strong> from submitting your application to having a working account.
        Do not plan to arrive with no banking and open an account the same week.
      </p>
      <p>
        Standard documentation requirements across the main banks:
      </p>
      <ul class="prose" style="padding-left: var(--space-6); margin-bottom: var(--space-4);">
        <li><strong>Employment letter</strong> from your Bermuda employer confirming your role, salary, and start date</li>
        <li><strong>Work permit</strong> (or evidence of permit application in process)</li>
        <li><strong>Proof of address in Bermuda</strong> — a signed tenancy agreement is usually accepted</li>
        <li><strong>Passport</strong> (primary ID)</li>
        <li><strong>Second form of ID</strong> — driving licence or national ID</li>
        <li>In some cases: reference letters from a bank in your home country</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Requirements vary between banks and can change. Contact the bank's personal banking team
        before you arrive to confirm the current list and to start the process remotely if possible.
        Some banks will allow you to initiate an application before you land.
        <VerifyBadge date="2026-06-10" sourceLabel="verify with each bank directly" sourceUrl="https://www.butterfieldgroup.com/bermuda" />
      </p>

      <!-- Currency -->
      <h2 style="margin-top: var(--space-10);">Currency — the Bermuda Dollar</h2>
      <p>
        Bermuda uses the <strong>Bermuda Dollar (BMD)</strong>, which is pegged at
        <strong>1:1 to the US Dollar</strong>. In practice, this means:
      </p>
      <ul class="prose" style="padding-left: var(--space-6); margin-bottom: var(--space-4);">
        <li>US dollars are accepted everywhere on the island, by every shop, restaurant, and service</li>
        <li>Bermuda Dollars and US Dollars are used interchangeably in daily life</li>
        <li>ATMs dispense both BMD and USD depending on the machine and settings</li>
        <li>When paying in cash, you may receive change in either currency — this is normal</li>
        <li>Bermuda Dollars cannot be used outside Bermuda; exchange them before you leave</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        For US-based expats, the 1:1 peg means there is no currency risk on your Bermuda salary
        relative to USD. For UK, Canadian, and European expats, the peg means your Bermuda income
        tracks the USD, which introduces some currency exposure on obligations back home.
      </p>

      <!-- Fees -->
      <h2 style="margin-top: var(--space-10);">Banking fees</h2>
      <p>
        Bermuda banks charge monthly account maintenance fees. This is different from the US online
        banking experience where many accounts are free to hold. Expect to pay a monthly fee for
        a standard current/checking account — typically in the $10–20/month range depending on
        the account type and bank.
      </p>
      <p>
        Premium account tiers (often called "Premier" or "Private Banking") at Butterfield and HSBC
        waive monthly fees in exchange for maintaining a minimum balance or meeting an asset threshold.
        If your employer offers a salary package that allows you to maintain a meaningful balance,
        investigate whether a premium tier makes sense.
      </p>
      <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--color-muted);">
        <span class="unverified">[Fee levels — verify current schedules directly with your chosen bank; they are subject to change.]</span>
      </p>

      <!-- International transfers -->
      <h2 style="margin-top: var(--space-10);">International transfers</h2>
      <p>
        International wire transfers from Bermuda bank accounts use the standard
        <strong>SWIFT/BIC</strong> system. Transfers to US accounts, UK accounts, and other major
        banking systems are routine and well-supported. The process is the same as a standard
        international wire from any other jurisdiction.
      </p>
      <p>
        Transfer fees vary by bank — typically $15–35 per outbound international wire.
        Processing times are 1–3 business days for most SWIFT transfers. If you are remitting
        money home regularly, ask your bank about the frequency fee structure and whether a
        standing-order arrangement reduces individual transaction costs.
      </p>

      <!-- Credit cards -->
      <h2 style="margin-top: var(--space-10);">Credit cards</h2>
      <p>
        Visa, Mastercard, and American Express are accepted at virtually all businesses in Bermuda —
        restaurants, hotels, shops, and most taxis. Contactless payments work. There is no meaningful
        cash-preference culture outside of a small number of local food stalls and market vendors.
        Your existing home-country credit cards will work without issue.
      </p>
      <p>
        Bermuda banks issue local credit cards, but many expats continue to use their home-country
        cards for rewards and because the local card products are not particularly competitive.
        Check your card's foreign transaction fee policy if you're using a US or UK card in Bermuda —
        some cards charge a 2–3% foreign transaction fee even though the BMD is at parity with USD.
      </p>

      <!-- US account warning -->
      <div style="background-color: var(--color-ink); color: var(--color-white); border-radius: var(--radius-lg); padding: var(--space-8); margin-top: var(--space-10);">
        <h2 style="color: var(--color-white); margin-bottom: var(--space-4); font-size: var(--text-2xl);">Important: US investment accounts and non-resident status</h2>
        <p style="color: rgba(255,255,255,0.85); margin-bottom: var(--space-4);">
          This is the issue that surprises US expats most. Once you become a non-US resident,
          some US-based financial institutions restrict or close accounts held by overseas residents.
        </p>
        <ul style="color: rgba(255,255,255,0.8); padding-left: var(--space-6); margin-bottom: var(--space-4);">
          <li style="margin-bottom: var(--space-2);">
            <strong>Fidelity, Vanguard, Schwab, and others</strong> have varying policies on accounts
            held by non-US residents. Some prohibit new purchases in existing brokerage accounts.
            Some close accounts or restrict access after you update your address to a non-US location.
          </li>
          <li style="margin-bottom: var(--space-2);">
            Policies differ by institution and by account type (brokerage vs. IRA vs. 401k).
            IRA and 401k accounts are generally more protected, but trading restrictions can still apply.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Check before you move.</strong> Update your address with your US financial institutions
            only after you understand what the consequences are. This is not a reason to conceal your
            address — it is a reason to understand the policy first and plan accordingly.
          </li>
        </ul>
        <p style="color: rgba(255,255,255,0.6); font-size: var(--text-sm); margin: 0;">
          <span class="unverified">[This is general information only. US financial regulation and individual institution policies change. Consult a qualified US tax and financial adviser before you move. This is not financial advice.]</span>
        </p>
      </div>

    </div>
  </div>
</Base>
